<HEADLINE>
FT  19 FEB 94 / Briefcase Q&amp;A: Exemption from CGT
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
I am out of work and receiving unemployment benefit plus a small
occupational pension which, because I am under 55, is untaxed. I do,
however, invest in both shares and traded options and am showing a
reasonable profit at the moment. I realise that capital gains tax is levied
at whatever rate of tax one pays on income, so could you confirm that, as a
non-taxpayer, my earnings on shares and options are exempt?
Someone whose income is too small to attract any income tax liability for
the present 1993-94 tax year is liable to pay capital gains tax on the
following scale: No CGT on the first Pounds 5,800; 20 per cent on the next
Pounds 2,500; 25 per cent on the next Pounds 21,200; 40 per cent on the
rest. Ask your tax office for the free introductory booklet to capital gains
tax, CGT14.
No legal responsibility can be accepted by the Financial Times for the
answers given in these columns. All enquiries will be answered by post as
soon as possible.
