<HEADLINE>
FT  19 FEB 94 / Briefcase Q&amp;A: Investing for grand-daughter
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
For nearly two years, I have been putting about Pounds 60 a month in an
investment trust savings scheme on behalf of my grand-daughter, now aged
four. The shares are in my name. I intend to continue investing until she is
18.
The investment will no doubt become a substantial sum while, at the same
time, producing significant dividends. Am I correct in assuming that,
provided her annual income does not exceed the single person's tax
allowance, she will be able to claim a tax refund on the dividends?
Also, when she receives the accumulated investment at 18, if/when she sells
the shares, will any associated capital gains be her responsibility and not
mine?
The fact that you have kept the shares in your own name (instead of simply
handing the monthly gifts of cash over to the girl's guardians for
investment on her behalf) might be taken as evidence that, although you plan
to give the shares to your granddaughter one day - when she is 18, for
example - they remain your own property at present.
You might wish to consult a solicitor about executing a declaration of trust
if there is no clear evidence of your bare trusteeship (such as a letter to
the girl's guardians and their consent to the shares being held in your name
rather than theirs). It could be, of course, that you consider the guardians
to be untrustworthy.
No legal responsibility can be accepted by the Financial Times for the
answers given in these columns. All enquiries will be answered by post as
soon as possible.
