<HEADLINE>
FT  19 FEB 94 / Global bond markets fall sharply on reports of heavy US
selling
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SARA WEBB and PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
World bond markets fell sharply yesterday afternoon as reports of heavy
selling by US investors created nervousness among international investors.
'There was an air of panic in the markets,' said Mr Nigel Richardson, head
of bond research at Yamaichi International (Europe), describing conditions
at one stage as a 'bloodbath'. Stocks were hit on Wall Street by a fall in
the US bond market.
The activity in Europe was mainly in the futures markets and bond dealers
said the main culprits were the US hedge funds - private pools of funds
which are managed very aggressively and are highly geared. Such funds were
buyers of European government bonds - particularly in the futures market -
last year and now appear to be liquidating their positions.
Dealers at US securities houses in London said rumours had swept the bond
markets of hedge funds being forced to close out their positions in order to
stem losses. 'There are rumours that some of the big hedge funds are in
trouble because they are highly leveraged players, and they are being forced
to liquidate their positions,' said one trader.
On Wall Street, longer-dated US Treasury bonds went into a steep fall for a
second consecutive session, prompting a sell-off on the share market.
Mixed news on inflation made the prospect of a second increase in short-term
interest rates loom larger, with Mr Alan Greenspan, the Federal Reserve
chairman, set to deliver his twice-yearly Humphrey-Hawkins testimony on
monetary policy to a congressional committee next Tuesday.
The yield on the 30-year Treasury bond climbed to 6.621 per cent, the first
time it has broken 6.60 per cent since last July. The Dow Jones Industrial
Average finished 35.18 lower at 3,887.46 on volume of 289m shares.
In the UK, analysts said the gilts market had not responded to economic
statistics, which pointed to low inflation and subdued growth. Gilt futures
closed down nearly 1 1/4 points. Bonds, Page 10
</TEXT>
