<HEADLINE>
FT  19 FEB 94 / Markets Report: D-Mark firmer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP GAWITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The trend of European interest rate cuts continued yesterday with Sweden,
Denmark, Finland and Spain following the example set by Germany on Thursday,
writes Philip Gawith.
Austria, the Netherlands, Belgium and Italy had already cut rates on
Thursday.
After weakening on Thursday, the D-Mark yesterday made up ground against
most European currencies as other countries cut rates. The market appeared
to be rewarding the easing of policy as being good for growth.
Elsewhere, sterling traded lower after disappointing lending figures
prompted concern about the strength of economic recovery, raising the
prospect of a further rate-cut.
In Europe the Danish central bank cut its discount and key deposit rate to
5.50 per cent from 5.75 per cent; Sweden cut its key marginal rate to 7.25
from 7.50 per cent; the Bank of Finland's money market tender rate fell to
4.75 from 4.95 per cent and the Bank of Spain reduced its daily intervention
rate by about 0.25 to around 8.55 per cent.
The Spanish cut surprised domestic money markets. Some analysts saw the
easing as a possible gesture to help Spain's fragile economic recovery.
The Danish Central Bank governor Mr Erik Hoffmeyer told Reuters in an
interview that having brought Danish key rates down to the same level as in
other European countries, Denmark would probably now follow the general
European downward trend in interest rates.
Mr Neil MacKinnon, chief economist at Citibank, said the stronger D-Mark was
a case of markets 'rewarding pro-growth policy initiatives.'
Mr Chris Turner, currency analyst at BZW, cautioned however against D-Mark
appreciation because of reflex pessimism about the likely pace of monetary
easing. 'If the D-Mark is going up because another cut is not seen for
another 4 months, then it's on dodgy ground.' Mr Turner said Germany looked
to be 'firmly back on the easing path.'
A feature of the European scene yesterday was the failure of the French
central bank to cut rates despite the depressed state of its economy. Mr
MacKinnon said a 'very significant' relaxation was required to ensure
economic recovery.
With the Bundesbank, however, expected to concentrate on steadying market
expectations rather than pursuing a path of dramatic cuts, he predicted
rates might not fall 'fast enough or to levels that are to the liking of the
French.'
Sterling closed yesterday at DM2.5406, down from DM2.5559 on Thursday. Part
of the weakness can be attributed to the the release of M4 bank and building
society figures - lending rose Pounds 200m in January compared to market
forecasts of a Pounds 2.5bn increase - suggesting that the private sector
remains unwilling to take on new debt.
A further factor weighing on sterling is the perception that UK rates may
well fall faster than those in Germany, following the Bundesbank's cautious
easing of policy on Thursday.
Sterling also finished stronger against the weak US dollar, closing in
London at Dollars 1.4788 from Dollars 1.474 on Thursday.
The Bank of England provided the UK money market with Pounds 900m of
assistance yesterday afternoon after not operating in the market in the
morning.
This assistance matched a forecast liquidity shortage of around Pounds 900m,
revised up from an earlier estimate of about Pounds 700m.
</TEXT>
