<HEADLINE>
FT  19 FEB 94 / Commodities and Agriculture (Week in the Markets): Aluminium
and copper  set pace
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD MOONEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Aluminium and copper continued to set the tone at the London Metal Exchange
this week and all base metals contracts finished higher.
Further output cut announcements by western aluminium producers (the latest
yesterday of 37,000 tonnes from Spain's Inespal) took the total since last
month's multilateral agreement in Brussels to 737,000 tonnes a year; and an
official of Russia's Aluminiy producer group helped to shore up a sometimes
shaky market with an assurance that his country's cuts, 100,000 tonnes a
year so far, would grow to 300,000 tonnes by the end of April.
Cheered by these developments, the market, which on Monday had tested
support at Dollars 1,230 a tonne for three months delivery, was able to
resume the uptrend that was interrupted last week. Yesterday morning three
months metal touched a fresh 18-month peak of Dollars 1,330 a tonne before
settling back to close at Dollars 1,321.50, up Dollars 56.50 on the week and
Dollars 149 since the conclusion of the Brussels meeting.
Three months copper surrendered Dollars 9 of its rise yesterday but still
ended Dollars 62 up on the week at Dollars 1,906.50 a tonne. Far Eastern
buying was the main influence in the rise and a substantial reduction in LME
warehouse stocks, though widely expected, helped to underpin the market. A
sustained fall has reduced exchange copper stocks by 52,950, or 8.5 per
cent, since mid-January.
Constructive chart patterns helped the zinc market to rally following the
heavy set-back caused by last week's news of the collapse of European
producers' efforts to forge an agreement for jointly financed output cuts.
After dipping to Dollars 948 a tonne on Tuesday the three months price
closed yesterday at Dollars 994.50, up Dollars 22 on the week.
A renewed uptrend in the tin market was fuelled by concern about supply
tightness developing for the early May delivery period. That resulted in
cash metal moving from a Dollars 52.50 discount against three months at the
end of last week to a Dollars 5 premium.
In the precious metals market the platinum price was yesterday knocked off a
five-year peak as selling spilled over from a weak gold market. The price
had been lifted to Dollars 404.50 a troy ounce in London by concern about
possible disruption to production during the South African election campaign
and Japanese buying encouraged by the weakness of the yen. But it was fixed
yesterday afternoon at Dollars 399 an ounce, still Dollars 9 to the good, as
the gold price plunged Dollars 7.50 to Dollars 378.50, near the bottom of
its recent trading range.
Oil prices were also very weak, with New York futures hitting five-year
lows. Traders said there were no particular developments to account for the
weakness of the market, which was still suffering from Opec inaction on
cutting excessive production.
At London's International Petroleum Exchange the prompt April futures
position, which dipped to Dollars 12.96 a barrel on Thursday morning, was
quoted in late trading yesterday at Dollars 13.20 a barrel, down 56 cents on
the week.
Technical rallies boosted both coffee and cocoa futures at the London
Commodity Exchange yesterday. May delivery coffee broke through resistance
at Dollars 1,228 a tonne and moved on to close at Dollars 1,243, up Dollars
16 on the day and Dollars 39 on the week. Cocoa, which had been trading in a
narrow range, put on a late spurt to end at Dollars 919 a tonne in the May
position, up Dollars 31 on the week.
