<HEADLINE>
FT  19 FEB 94 / International Company News: Austrian carriers in share deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK BLUM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   VIENNA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Austrian Airlines will buy a 42.85 per cent stake in Tyrolean Airways, the
country's second largest scheduled flights operator. The deal, which must be
approved by the companies' boards, is a further step towards restructuring
the country's airline industry and will strengthen the Austrian national
carrier's position in negotiations over co-operation with Lufthansa.
Under the transaction the share capital of Tyrolean Airways will be
increased by 50 per cent to Sch135m (Dollars 11.1m). Austrian is believed to
have paid close to Sch300m for its stake in the small but profitable
Tyrolean, whose Innsbruck-based operations have successfully served as a
regional hub for business and leisure traffic. Last year Tyrolean carried
510,000 passengers providing a turnover of about Sch1bn.
Mr Rudolf Steicher, chairman of Austrian's supervisory board, said the move
would strengthen both companies. Other shareholders will be Gernot
Langes-Swarovski, the fine crystal and glass manufacturer, with 42.85 per
cent and Leipnik Lundenburger Industrie, pulp and paper producer, with 14.3
per cent.
The services of the two airlines will be integrated using Tyrolean's 13
aircraft and 10 of Austrian's fleet - ones which are dedicated to regional
services within Austria and to short-range international destinations such
as Budapest and Zurich. The 23 aircraft will carry about 1.2m passengers.
Austrian is seeking co-operation with Lufthansa following the collapse of
attempts to set up a joint airline with Swissair, Scandinavian Airlines
Systems and KLM.
</TEXT>
