<HEADLINE>
FT  19 FEB 94 / Lambeth dubbed a 'shambles' by chief
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
There was 'a shambles at the very heart of the organisation' of Lambeth
Borough Council mid-way through last year, Mr Henry Gilby, the London
borough's chief executive, has told councillors, John Authers writes.
He recommends department mergers and redundancies as part of the changes
needed in the borough. Only eight directorates would report to the chief
executive rather than the present 13.
The changes would be part of Lambeth's attempt to answer criticisms in a
report by the district auditor last year, which found that Pounds 20.2m had
been spent unlawfully.
Mr Gilby says the council's central support services unit for members is
'wholly unsatisfactory, confused and overmanaged', and 'developed in an ad
hoc way that does not directly relate to the requirements of this section'.
The corporate standards unit - charged with co-ordinating policy - 'had not
had an appointed head for nearly two years' and its work had not been
satisfactorily dealt with. The equalities unit 'has not had an appointed
head for a very considerable period'. This meant that equalities had become
marginalised. The two units would be merged.
The information services and finance services departments would also be
merged.
The report is still at the draft stage and must be approved by councillors
before further management action can be taken.
