<HEADLINE>
FT  19 FEB 94 / Venezuela bails out ailing banks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOSEPH MANN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CARACAS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Four Venezuelan financial institutions are receiving government aid because
of liquidity problems, Mr Julio Sosa, Venezuela's minister of finance, said
yesterday.
Testifying before a congressional committee on the state of Venezuela's
financial system, he said three of the troubled entities were commercial
banks.
Venezuela's financial system is still reeling from the effects of the
failure of the country's second largest bank, Banco Latino. The government
took control of Banco Latino in the middle of last month. With the help of
several large banks, it has provided Latino and other troubled banks with
over Dollars 1bn.
Bankers in Caracas say privately that more than four financial institutions
are in trouble and that a series of government measures announced this week
are not sufficient to confront the financial system's problems.
These measures included a determination to re-float Latino, a government
demand that banks receiving official financial assistance increase their
capital bases and improve performance, and a plan to strengthen the
country's bank regulatory system. Last month, the central bank reportedly
had eleven financial institutions on its 'watch list'.
President Rafael Caldera said yesterday he was replacing Roger Urbina, the
superintendent of banks, which regulates and supervises the system, and
Esperanza Martino, president of the Deposit Insurance Fund.
</TEXT>
