<HEADLINE>
FT  18 FEB 94 / Commodities and Agriculture: Norwegians dismiss call to ease
tax burden
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN FOSSLI
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   OSLO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Norwegian petroleum authorities have rejected calls made by a
government-appointed working group for an easing in the country's stringent
tax regime
The working group, established last May, warned that a major overhaul of
petroleum operations to cut industry costs by up to 50 per cent over a
five-year period would be necessary if Norway was to remain competitive with
other producing nations once crude oil production fell sharply in the
mid-1990s.
Norway, western Europe's biggest oil producer, currently produces about 2.4m
barrels of crude a day.
In a report delivered on Wednesday to Mr Jens Stoltenberg, the industry and
energy minister, Mr Torleif Enger, leader of the group and an executive with
Norsk Hydro, Norway's biggest listed company, said it could already be
possible for oil companies operating in Norway to reduce costs by up to 30
per cent for fields now being developed by implementing measures such as
standardising equipment for field developments, improving cost analyses,
reducing documentation and duplication of engineering.
But the report said that current profitability of operations on the
Norwegian continental shelf was not sufficient to secure the competitive
position of the shelf internationally.
Mr Stoltenberg expected to respond to the report in a white paper on the
future of Norway's petroleum industry, due to be presented to the Storting
in a few weeks. But he said this would not address complaints about the tax
regime. The report said that while oil prices were significantly lower than
at the time the tax regime was established in 1975, the tax level was
significantly higher.
