<HEADLINE>
FT  18 FEB 94 / Commodities and Agriculture: Rice - the next generation /
Scientists are pinning their hopes on an entirely new variety that could
increase yields by 20-25 per cent
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MADELEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
While the dramatic rise in the world price of rice - by almost 100 per cent
since last September - could stimulate increased production, scientists at
the Manila-based International Rice Research Institute are warning that
existing rice varieties are unlikely to yield more.
The high-yielding varieties developed in the late 1960s - under the so
called 'green revolution' - have peaked, the scientists say. 'Increases in
rice production have flowed dramatically since 1985 in the 10 countries that
account for 85 per cent of world production,' says IRRI economist Mr Mahabub
Hossain.
Nearly 90 per cent of all the world's rice is grown and eaten in Asia; about
60 per cent is under irrigation. Only about 3 per cent of global output is
traded internationally.
Scientists are now pinning their hopes on a completely new rice plant that
could yield 20-25 per cent more than existing irrigated varieties.
According to the IRRI's estimates, rice output will have to increase by 70
per cent in the next 25 years to keep up with demand. This means that an
extra 350m tonnes a year will have to be grown. But because of competing
demands on resources in the year 2020 rice will have to be grown on less
land, using less water.
Most rice in Asia grows standing in water, but it appears that the water
robs soil of oxygen and eventually erodes its fertility. IRRI scientists
estimate that in southern Asia alone, about 10m hectares of highly
productive rice land - 10 per cent of the global area under irrigated rice -
is showing signs of fatigue.
'Under submerged conditions, there appears to be a reduction in the amount
of nitrogen the soil can provide to the crop,' explains Mr Ken Cassman, head
of IRRI's agronomy, plant physiology and agroecology division.
The new rice could help solve this problem. To develop the variety IRRI
scientists searched the Institute's extensive collection of germplasm for
the characteristics they wanted in the new plant. Some samples, for example,
can make good use of naturally available nitrogen; some can produce a larger
number of grains per panicle - the part of the plant that carries the rice
grain; others have good resistance to pest and plant diseases.
By crossing these samples, scientists combined the traits to produce the
plant they wanted. This is now being tested in IRRI's fields and the crop is
due to be harvested this May.
IRRI's chief plant breeder, Mr Gurdev Khush, says that the new rice plant
'differs from existing varieties in several ways. It has fewer tillers
(stems) but larger panicles'. He hopes that the new plant will yield up to
12-12.5 tonnes a hectare under irrigated conditions.
Mr Khush admits there are several problems the new plant may face - taste,
for example. As taste preferences vary from country to country the new rice
will have to adapt to local requirements.
IRRI's deputy director-general in charge of research, Mr Ken Fischer,
believes that with more research the new rice could yield up to 15 tonnes a
hectare within a decade, half as much again as existing varieties.
There could be even larger gains from rain-fed lowland areas. Some 38m
hectares of lowland rice in Asia - 40 per cent of the total area under rice
 -have no irrigation. Rice production in most of Bangladesh, Cambodia,
Eastern India and Laos depends on the rain.
The 'green revolution' has bypassed farmers in these areas. They continue to
grow traditional varieties that yield only 1.5 to 2.5 tonnes a hectare. Poor
soils and adverse climate - sometimes both drought and floods in the same
cropping season - make for limited incomes, which means farmers cannot
afford to purchase inputs such as fertilisers. A variation of the new rice
plant is being developed for these areas.
Because local conditions vary a great deal, research for this plant has been
done by rice institutes in the countries where lowland rice is dominant. The
first plant will be tested later this year in Eastern India.
Mr Robert Zeigler, leader of IRRI's rain-fed lowland rice ecosystem
programme, says the rain-fed area plant will need to yield well, develop a
good root system, tolerate drought and submersion under water and be able to
cope with weeds.
'If we can develop the right traits,' he says, 'then farmers will be more
inclined to invest in fertiliser and increase their yields.' He believes
that the research could bring significant results within the next five years
and that yields from rain-fed lowlands could triple, to over 5 tonnes a
hectare.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>XOZ  Asia.
</CN>
<XX>
