<HEADLINE>
FT  18 FEB 94 / World Commodities Prices: Wool
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Wool sales held in the past week presented a mixed picture. Superfine
merinos were dearer at Australian sales which included limited offerings of
these categories. With future supplies this season negligible and little
held in stock competition was intense, even while demand for other merinos
tended to ebb a little. The overall Australian market indicator ended the
week at 523 cents, 23 cents below its peak earlier this month. Wool sold
well in New Zealand and South Africa meanwhile, and special circumstances
helped to underline strength in prices paid for British wool, already
considered relatively dear internationally. The trade in general is showing
reluctance to sell more cheaply or act on the assumption that wool prices
may not rise further soon.
