<HEADLINE>
FT  18 FEB 94 / International Company News: Euro Disney banks to get final
audit data on Monday
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Euro Disney banks on Monday will receive the final version of an
investigative audit of the troubled leisure group's finances from KPMG Peat
Marwick, the accountancy firm, and will then call a meeting with Euro Disney
to begin negotiations over its emergency financial restructuring.
Next week's meeting will follow a formal meeting in Paris earlier this week
in which the banks discussed preliminary proposals for the restructuring
with senior executives of Euro Disney and Walt Disney, the US entertainment
company that owns 49 per cent of its equity.
However, the banks had on Monday only seen a draft version of the KPMG
report, which analyses Euro Disney's current financial position and future
capital requirements. As a result they were not able to begin full-scale
discussions with the Disney camp.
KPMG yesterday confirmed that all Euro Disney's 60 banks will receive the
final audit on Monday thereby enabling them to begin formal negotiations at
a meeting later in the week.
The banks have formed a steering committee, led by Banque Nationale de Paris
and Banque Indosuez, to negotiate directly with Euro Disney, advised by S.
G. Warburg in London, and Walt Disney, advised by Lazard Freres in New York.
Walt Disney has asked the banks to agree to halve Euro Disney's FFr20.3bn
(Dollars 3.39bn) debt through the combination of a rights issue and
debt-for-equity swap. However, the preliminary findings of the KPMG audit
suggest that Euro Disney will require a higher capital injection of between
FFr12bn and FFr13bn.
The banks are keen to ensure that the US group plays a larger part in the
restructuring. They plan to press Walt Disney to make concessions such as
reducing its royalty payments from Euro Disney which were worth FFr262m last
year.
The banks have also asked KPMG to scrutinise Euro Disney's corporate
strategy to assess whether there should be changes in senior personnel and
operating policy. KPMG declined to comment on whether it would be presenting
its corporate analysis on Monday alongside the financial audit.
</TEXT>
