<HEADLINE>
FT  18 FEB 94 / UK Company News: Operating strength lifts A McAlpine shares
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR and MARC JONES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The share price of Alfred McAlpine jumped by 35p to 329p yesterday after the
construction group announced a better than expected operating performance
for the year to October 31.
As expected, provisions of Pounds 6.5m were made to cover potential losses
on a housing joint venture, construction contracts, reorganisation, and a
Pounds 500,000 loss on disposals.
These reduced pre-tax profits to Pounds 1.17m, against Pounds 3.39m restated
for FRS 3. Turnover rose from Pounds 560.7m to Pounds 620.7m.
Before exceptional items, profits rose from Pounds 5.4m to Pounds 7.7m. This
was after an interest bill of Pounds 3.33m (Pounds 2.66m).
The improvement was led by the housing division, which after interest more
than doubled profits to Pounds 5.51m (Pounds 2.58m).
Mr Oliver Whitehead, chief executive, said the recovery in the UK housing
market had seen higher sales and improved margins and was 'unlikely to be
upset by higher tax bills due to take effect in April'.
Earnings per share before exceptional items increased to 9.6p (7.3p). After
taking account of provisions, earnings fell from to 4.8p to 0.7p. The final
dividend is maintained at 3.5p, for a same-again total of 6.5p.
The number of homes completed rose by a fifth to 1,521. The average price
remained static at Pounds 79,400. Mr Whitehead expected prices to rise over
the next 12 months to Pounds 90,000.
Profits from contracting rose marginally to Pounds 3.03m (Pounds 2.9m) in
spite of an 8 per cent rise in construction turnover to Pounds 371.5m,
reflecting low margins. UK aggregate profits fell from Pounds 1.86m to
Pounds 1.19m.
In the US, profits from contracting and building materials were lower than
expected at Pounds 1.68m (Pounds 1.84m).
The group is changing its year end to December 31.
COMMENT
The fillip in McAlpine's share price had as much to do with optimism about
the company's prospects as with market satisfaction over a better than
expected operating performance. Margins on housing are rising
satisfactorily, without some of the big write-downs announced by other
builders. This means the company has more to gain as it uses up expensive
land acquired in the late 1980s. Management also appears to have a tight
grip on the construction business and is confident that it will avoid
serious problems on low margin contracts caused by rising building material
prices. The US business remains strong and the group should be capable of
making Pounds 13m in the current year and up to Pounds 19m in 1994-95. This
would put McAlpine on a prospective p/e of 14 times earnings two years on,
making the shares still look reasonably attractive in a sector which is at a
substantial premium to the rest of the market.
</TEXT>
