<HEADLINE>
FT  18 FEB 94 / Pension transfer hope for state workers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH and NORMA COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Thousands of public sector workers who transferred into private pension
plans could find it easier to be readmitted to their old schemes under a
possible change in the law being considered by the government.
The move, which follows widespread concern about potential mis-selling of
pension transfers, would be directed at former members of statute-based
occupational schemes, such as that in the National Health Service.
Public sector pension schemes offer some of the best benefits in the UK,
including inflation-linked pension payments and early retirement provisions.
However, members of some schemes were targeted by insurance agents who sold
them private plans.
Some schemes, such as the Mineworkers' Pension Scheme, are already allowing
former members back in, though they will be reinstated in full only if they
bring an amount to cover their missing contributions. Other large
occupational schemes have said they will not consider re-admission.
The government is likely to reject suggestions from some regulators and
parts of the life insurance industry that legislation should be used to
encourage private sector schemes to re-admit former members. But any change
in the law would be intended to put pressure on public and private sector
schemes to accept back former members who suffered as a result of poor
advice and wished to rejoin.
The most likely prospect for legislation would be a provision in a bill on
the recommendations of the Goode committee on occupational pensions, which
the Department of Social Security hopes will be included in the 1994-95
parliamentary session.
A working group set up by the Securities and Investments Board, the chief
City regulator, is expected in July to report how the industry should
recompense customers who have suffered.
Unease about the selling of pension transfers surfaced late last year after
a study by the accountancy firm, KPMG Peat Marwick, suggested that in nine
out of 10 cases, regulators' standards had not been met.
</TEXT>
