<HEADLINE>
FT  18 FEB 94 / Observer: Correlational correctness
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Some interest rate-watchers swear by the money supply figures; others watch
the exchange rate. But Midland Bank's Alison Cottrell, 29, who has lived far
too long in Roger Bootle's shadow, prefers to check the calendar of
international events. Yesterday's cut in the Bundesbank discount rate
suggests she may be on to something.
Cottrell has been counting the number of times that the Bundesbank fiddles
with its interest rates just before a big economic happening. 'It's like sun
spots. You know they don't mean anything but they sometimes work,' says
Cottrell. When she heard that the next G7 finance ministers' meeting was to
be in Frankfurt on February 26, she let everyone know she smelt an interest
rate cut.
What next? Cottrell has put red rings round the Bundesbank meetings on April
28, a few days after the IMF's spring bash in Washington, and May 26, a few
days before the OECD's annual jamboree. 'Correlation is not causation, but
who cares?' says Cottrell. Sound thinking.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>DEZ  Germany, EC.
